ributor contributorType="Producer"><contributorName nameType="Personal">Vohra, Sunita</contributorName><givenName>Sunita</givenName><familyName>Vohra</familyName><affiliation>University of Alberta</affiliation></contributor></contributors><dates><date dateType="Created">2011</date><date dateType="Updated">2017-05-29</date><date dateType="Collected">2011-01/2013-04</date></dates><resourceType resourceTypeGeneral="Dataset">Interview data; Brain imaging data; Survey data</resourceType><alternateIdentifiers><alternateIdentifier alternateIdentifierType="ClinicalTrials.gov">NCT01307943</alternateIdentifier></alternateIdentifiers><version>1.2</version><rightsList><rights rightsURI="info:eu-repo/semantics/openAccess"/><rights/></rightsList><descriptions><description descriptionType="Abstract">Mindfulness-based stress reduction (MBSR) is a group program in which participants are taught to be mindful or present-focused. MBSR programs consist of instruction in a variety of mindfulness meditations including body scan, sitting meditation, mindful yoga, and discussion of these practices. The purpose of this study was to develop and conduct a pilot mixed-methods randomized controlled trial (RCT), combining clinical outcomes, qualitative interviews, and brain imaging to assess the impact of the intervention on children with mental health challenges.</description></descriptions><geoLocations><geoLocation><geoLocationPlace>Edmonton, Alberta</geoLocationPlace></geoLocation></geoLocations></resource>